{"cursor":"28191","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Steal}}\n\nThievery|Theft (disambiguation)}}\n\n\n\nIn common usage, 'theft' is the taking of another person's property without that\nperson's permission or consent with the intent to deprive the rightful owner of\nit. The word is\nalso used as an informal shorthand term for some crimes against property, such\nas burglary, embezzlement, larceny, looting, robbery, shoplifting and fraud. In some jurisdictions, theft is\nconsidered to be synonymous with larceny; in\nothers, theft has replaced larceny. Someone who carries out an act of or makes a\ncareer of theft is known as a 'thief.' The act of theft is known by terms such\nas 'stealing', 'thieving,' and 'filching.'\n\nTheft is the name of a statutory offence in California, Canada, England and\nWales, Hong Kong,[http://www.legislation.gov.hk/blis_pdf.nsf/6799165D2FEE3FA948-\n25755E0033E532/AC628B0C8930CE4F482575EE004D2B22?OpenDocument&bt=0] Northern\nIreland, the Republic of Ireland, and Victoria.\n","linknr":685,"url":"Theft","recorded":1362570591,"links":71,"instances":["law","law","australia","criminal","casinos","property","northern_ireland_1969","law","criminal_law","law"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Crimes","Sins","Theft|","Law"],"headings":["Elements","By country","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Germany_in_XXI_century._Criminal_police.jpg/220px-Germany_in_XXI_century._Criminal_police.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Fortunes_of_a_Street_Waif.jpg/220px-Fortunes_of_a_Street_Waif.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Theft-p1000763.jpg/220px-Theft-p1000763.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common